              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1384944-ron-charles?shelf=war-fiction">war-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1384944-ron-charles?shelf=2017-favorites">2017-favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1986135686" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer940006571886829963">Truly, this is a remarkable creation, a story both intimate and international, swelling with comedy and outrage, a tale that cradles the world’s most fragile people even while it assaults the Subcontinent’s most brutal villains.<br/><br/>It will not convert Roy’s political enemies, but it will surely blast past them. Here are sentences that feel athletic enough to sprint on for pages, feinting in different directions at once, dropping disparate allusions, tossing off witty asides, refracting competing iro</span>
  <span id="freeText940006571886829963" style="display:none">Truly, this is a remarkable creation, a story both intimate and international, swelling with comedy and outrage, a tale that cradles the world’s most fragile people even while it assaults the Subcontinent’s most brutal villains.<br /><br />It will not convert Roy’s political enemies, but it will surely blast past them. Here are sentences that feel athletic enough to sprint on for pages, feinting in different directions at once, dropping disparate allusions, tossing off witty asides, refracting competing ironies. This is writing that swirls so hypnotically that it doesn’t feel like words on paper so much as ink in water. Every paragraph dares you to keep up, forcing you finally to stop asking questions, to stop grasping for chronology and just. . . . <br /><br /><i>To read the rest of this review, go The Washington Post:</i><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/books/after-a-20-years-arundhati-roy-returns-with-a-gem-the-ministry-of-utmost-happiness/2017/05/30/ae97f5d8-3fd6-11e7-9869-bac8b446820a_story.html">https://www.washingtonpost.com/entert...</a></span>
