    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2270225623" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2270225623" />
    <a title="Khush" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/76759105-khush"><img alt="Khush" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/m_50x66-82093808bca726cb3249a493fbd3bd0f.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2270225623?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Khush" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Khush" href="/user/show/76759105-khush">Khush</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2270225623" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14597698969698802424"><br/><br/><br/><br/>This book took twenty years to get written. It is big a book with a great many characters, incidents, issues; it primarily tells the story of Anjum a &apos;Hijra&apos; (transgender) from Delhi. Roy writes beautifully about the story of this &apos;Hijra&apos; child from the time it is born. The child is called &apos;Aftab&apos;, at the threshold of adolescence, Aftab becomes Anjum and leaves home to join a group of &apos;Hijras&apos; in old Delhi.<br/><br/>The first part of the book is its best. It takes us to the innermost crevices of the city,</span>
  <span id="freeText14597698969698802424" style="display:none"><br /><br /><br /><br />This book took twenty years to get written. It is big a book with a great many characters, incidents, issues; it primarily tells the story of Anjum a 'Hijra' (transgender) from Delhi. Roy writes beautifully about the story of this 'Hijra' child from the time it is born. The child is called 'Aftab', at the threshold of adolescence, Aftab becomes Anjum and leaves home to join a group of 'Hijras' in old Delhi.<br /><br />The first part of the book is its best. It takes us to the innermost crevices of the city, to those who live on streets and still are invisible as if they do not matter. The city of Delhi and the body of 'Hijra' seem almost synonymous. Just like the city of Delhi, the Hijras are often loud, vulgar and unforgiving. Just like the city has its own unhidden charms, so does the Hijra. In the case of Anjum, she has to live in the graveyard. Nobody wants her. Roy refers to this place as 'the Ministry of utmost Happiness.' Not ironically but quite literally. With the exception of a few joyful moments in the graveyard, the rest is misery; a story of intense struggles especially of those discarded by the hostile city.<br /><br />The book begins with the story of Delhi and Anjum, the transgender, and then goes on to tell the cruelties of the Indian city on Kashmiris in the North and the tribals in central India. <br /><br />What is wrong with this book is that it seeks to say ALL about India. Roy has tried to contain this giant beast called India in over 400 pages. The book fails her. The second half of the book reads like excellent journalism. Roy, speaking at different venues in Europe, claims that she intended the structure of this book very carefully; nothing happens accidentally and what seems like chaos and excessive is part of the larger design. This only sounds like a brilliant excuse for a writing that has gone out of hand; she starts with a story and ends up writing a book that reads like non-fiction..<br /><br />The readers who are not familiar with India and its politics may find it even harder to finish this book. However, if one wants to know the truth about what has been going on in India since 1990s, especially in Kashmir, one should read this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14597698969698802424" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

